Qualitative Coding:
-students are making filters in their district groups using materials they "bought" (using sand dollars?)

-students are on a field trip to observe a water treatment plant
-signal (3:12) towards the beginning of the video for some reason
-the video is mainly students just observing what goes on in a water treatment plant as an expert gives a lecture on what is happening
-some students do generate their own questions for the expert as they walk around the facilities

-students continue to ask the expert at the water treament facility questions
-observing an empty tank in the facility
-they also observe the water in a different tank at the facility and then the expert talks about the whole process of cleaning the water one last time
-teacher points out that the students should observe the how the water looks cleaner
-finally they observe the disinfection tank and many note how it smells like chlorine 
----they had learned that later the chlorine must be neutralized because it can be harmful to some of the animals living in the bay (which is where the water ultimately goes) so some pointed out that there were ducks on the water and wondered if that was bad for them (observations, asking questions)

-Teachers put "1972" on the board and the students are asked to guess what is significant about the year (this was an introduction to the topic of saving the bay and keeping it clean aka clean water act)
-their class seems to have the theme of environmental sustainability and eco-friendliness
-while the teacher is lecturing she asks the students many questions and encourages them to give their best answer even if they don't necessarily know (interpreting and communicating findings)
----many of her questions are asking them to think more deeply about the topics, which is likely the "interpreting" aspect
-they are also observing a life size model of a seal that the teacher is giving information about, while continuing to prompt the students with questions

-the seal has model organs inside, so the students continue making observations about the seal's internal organs
-the stomach actually has small animals inside representing the seal's diet!
-the seal's stomach also includes a plastic bag, and the teacher prompts students to think about why that would happen and how that effects the animal (going along with their theme of eco-friendliness)
----she asks what "we as a society" has done to reduce the amount of plastic bags
-the students are also asking questions about the model seal
-one student asked if the seal had a baby inside, and the other students dismissed the question as dumb. HOWEVER, later on it turns out that there is a small baby inside, which leads the teacher to talk about the development of the seal
-students are asked to bring up the salinity of a container of water in their district groups (experiment is not shown in the segment of film because of the signal and survey, only some directions are shown)
----each group is given a large sheet of paper to bring back to school with them (reason unclear)

-students are counting in their districts how much plastic they gathered (from one of their field trip sites at the bay?)
-they are asked to write down the amount of plastic each district gathered (recording data!)
-they are then sharing their findings with each other based on calculations (analysis?) they did with the data
----they were calculating how many pieces of plastic they collected together over four days (134 pieces)
----she then asks them to calculate how many pieces they would have collected over four weeks
----she has them talk through the process of how to calculate this out loud to the whole class, and after some discussion and the students have still not come up with a solution after the teacher prompts them with more questions she has them discuss in their smaller groups
----the teachers want them to understand why certain calculations work

-first the teacher is just lecturing on some material (the geography of Rhode Island and how the rivers lead into the bay and the effect of pollution in those rivers)
